data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code for .NET 8.

## Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `while (_running)` loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `IsCancellationRequested` |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` in `Stop()` | Force stop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `GetNextItem()` may block | Blocking call interruption | Pass token to unblock |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);       // pass token for checkpoint checks
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent of the old ThreadAbortException catch —
                // clean up partial work, then let the loop exit naturally.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control whether to continue or exit
                // via the loop condition. The loop will exit because the token
                // is cancelled.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts == null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals all token checks to stop

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

**`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`**
`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. Cancellation is now *cooperative* — your code must voluntarily check the token.

**`ThreadAbortException` → `OperationCanceledException`**
Token-aware APIs throw `OperationCanceledException` when cancelled. The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter avoids catching unrelated exceptions.

**`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed**
No equivalent needed. You control flow with the loop condition. If you *wanted* to continue processing after a cancellation (like `ResetAbort` allowed), you'd create a new `CancellationTokenSource` per work item.

**`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `Thread.Join(TimeSpan)`**
`Join` is the correct way to wait for a thread to finish — `Sleep` was just hoping it would end in time.

**`volatile bool _running` → removed**
`CancellationToken` replaces the manual flag. It's thread-safe and integrates with blocking APIs.

## Critical: You Must Update `GetNextItem`

The old code relied on `Thread.Abort` to forcibly interrupt `GetNextItem()` when it was blocking. **Cooperative cancellation cannot interrupt a blocking call that ignores the token.** You must pass the token through:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could break it
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks forever if queue is empty
}

// AFTER — unblocks when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep`, `WaitHandle.WaitOne`, or similar:

```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep with cancellation-aware wait
Thread.Sleep(1000);                  // ❌ not cancellable
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000);      // ✅ wakes on cancel

// Replace WaitHandle.WaitOne with token-aware overload
event.WaitOne();                                         // ❌
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle });   // ✅
```

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---------|--------|
| Not passing token to `GetNextItem` | Thread hangs forever on `Stop()` — the whole point of the migration breaks |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it | Masks cancellation; let it propagate except at the top-level loop |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks timers and callbacks — always `Dispose()` in `Stop()` |
| Assuming cancellation is instant | It only fires at the next `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or token-aware API call |
| Long gaps between token checks in `ProcessItem` | Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints inside expensive work |
